UCI breast cancer dataset

Additional information available here: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/breast-cancer-wisconsin/breast-cancer-wisconsin.names

The dataset consists of 699 cells for which you have the following features: 1. Sample code number: id number 2. Clump Thickness: 1 - 10 3. Uniformity of Cell Size: 1 - 10 4. Uniformity of Cell Shape: 1 - 10 5. Marginal Adhesion: 1 - 10 6. Single Epithelial Cell Size: 1 - 10 7. Bare Nuclei: 1 - 10 8. Bland Chromatin: 1 - 10 9. Normal Nucleoli: 1 - 10 10. Mitoses: 1 - 10 11. Class: (2 for benign, 4 for malignant)

Loading data

data1 <- read_csv("~/Downloads/breast-cancer-wisconsin.data.txt", col_names = FALSE)

Renaming variables per code book

# Renaming variables according to those given in code book
new_names <- c("id", "clump_thickness", "cell_size_uniformity", "cell_shape_uniformity",
               "marginal_adhesion", "single_epi_cell_size", "bare_nuclei", "bland_chromatin",
               "normal_nucleoli", "mitoses", "class")
names(data1) <- new_names

Checking for and dealing with missing data

# There are several variables that are missing values, and we may need to replace them later.
# How many missing values are there?
colSums(is.na(data1))
##                    id       clump_thickness  cell_size_uniformity 
##                     0                     0                     0 
## cell_shape_uniformity     marginal_adhesion  single_epi_cell_size 
##                     0                     0                     0 
##           bare_nuclei       bland_chromatin       normal_nucleoli 
##                    16                     0                     0 
##               mitoses                 class 
##                     0                     0
# Only bare nuclei is missing values. Options for imputation include mean imputation and KNN imputation.
# Mean imputation is an option but we'll use another method that may be better than mean imputation given how little we know about this data.

# Using KNN imputation to replace 16 missing values for the bare_nuclei variable.
# This First subsetting out the 9 independent variables away from the ID variable and the 'class' dependent variable
data2 <- data.frame(data1[,2:11])
# Imputing the missing values
data3 <- knnImputation(data2, k = 3)
# The imputation made the bare_nuclei variable into a float. To respect the integer structure of the variable and preserve its scale, we'll change the imputed variable back into an integer by first rounding it and then converting
# it back to an integer.
data3$bare_nuclei <- round(data3$bare_nuclei)
data3$bare_nuclei <- as.integer(data3$bare_nuclei)
# recombining the imputed independent variables back with the dependent variable.
data4 <- data.frame(data1["id"], data3)

Recoding dependent variable

# Recoding dependent variable of class
# Recoding dependent variable from 2 and 4 to 0 and 1. 2 is benign and 4 is malignant according to the UCI code book for
# this data found here:
# https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/breast-cancer-wisconsin/breast-cancer-wisconsin.names
data4$class <- ifelse(data4$class == 4, 1, 0)

Checking for class imbalance in dependent variable

table(data4$class)
## 
##   0   1 
## 458 241
# There are considerably fewer malignant cells in the data set than benign cells. This could be problematic for analysis and options for upsampling and downsampling should be explored. Despite the small size of the data set, downsampling might be a better option since upsampling would mean creating artifical data on malignant cancer cells. Since the imputed data is the class of interest and concerns health, downsampling is the first option to explore. KNN imputation of 16 values of the bare_nuclei variable is somewhat less of a concern than imputing hundreds of observations worth of data on malignant cells.

Spearman correlation calculation and heatmap plot of the results

spearman_data1 = cor(data4[,2:11], method="spearman")
melted_spearman = melt(spearman_data1)
ggplot(melted_spearman, aes(Var1, Var2)) + # x and y axes => Var1 and Var2
  geom_tile(aes(fill = value)) + # background colours are mapped according to the value column
  geom_text(aes(fill = melted_spearman$value, label = round(melted_spearman$value, 2))) + # write the values
  scale_fill_gradient2(low = muted("darkred"), 
                       mid = "white", 
                       high = muted("midnightblue"), 
                       midpoint = 0) + # determine the color

Preliminary analyses - part 1 - multidimensional scaling

# A google search of the data analysis of cancer cells reveals that multidimensional scaling is typically used
# to simplify differences between cell data.
# source: https://www.researchgate.net/figure/6708184_fig1_Figure-1-Multidimensional-scaling-of-cell-line-and-tumor-data-A-428-dimensional-data
#
# Non-metric MDS is for ordinal data, and judging from the number of variables concerning shape and size in this data,
# we'll use non-metric MDS instead of metric MDS
# An error is thrown because row 208 and 209 are identical. Subsetting out duplicate rows.
data5 <- distinct(data4)
dim(data5)
## [1] 691  11
# Several additional rows were removed!
# Attempting MDS again
d <- dist(data5) # euclidean distances between the rows
fit <- isoMDS(d, k=2) # k is the number of dimensions we'll use. We'll choose 2 for the purposes of visualization since these
## initial  value 0.000003 
## final  value 0.000003 
## converged
# analyses are preliminary.
# Visualization of multidimensional scaling
x <- fit$points[,1]
y <- fit$points[,2]
plot(x, y, xlab="Coordinate 1", ylab="Coordinate 2", 
     main="Nonmetric MDS", type="n")
text(x, y, labels = data5$id, cex=.7)

# Looks like 8233704 and 123454352 can be dropped.
# first combining x and y in data frame for use with second analytic method
fit_dataFrame <- as.data.frame(cbind(x, y, data5["class"]), row.names = NULL, optional = FALSE, cut.names = FALSE,
              col.names = c("x", "y"), fix.empty.names = TRUE,
              stringsAsFactors = default.stringsAsFactors())
# Checking index positions of these observations
which(data5$id == 8233704)
## [1] 524
which(data5$id == 13454352)
## [1] 656
# Based on positions
fit1_dataFrame <- fit_dataFrame[-(which(data5$id == 8233704)),]
# Removing id# 123454352, adjusting index for removal of id# 8233704
fit1_dataFrame <- fit1_dataFrame[-(which(data5$id == 13454352) - 1),]

Preliminary analyses - Part 2 - KNN

Achieves good accuracy.

# The UCI data book mentions two papers, one of which mentions that three hyperplanes describes the data separation very well.
# There are only two classes in the dependent variable. There is a newish technique that uses multiple hyperplanes in a
# support vector machine kernel called an adaptive multi-hyperplane machine. There are implementations in Matlab and C++
#
# The Second research paper mentions the use of instance-based methods. This will work out well because the data set is small
# and instance-based methods require the full dataset for prediction. The simplest and most popular instance based method is
# K nearest neighbors. We'll try that using the multidimensional scaling results.
#
fit1_split <- createDataPartition(y = fit1_dataFrame$class, p = 0.7, list = FALSE)
training <- fit1_dataFrame[fit1_split,]
test <- fit1_dataFrame[-fit1_split,]
# On visual inspection of the plot of the multidimensional scaling, there appears to be 2-4 clusters. However, we'll let cross
# validation pick the best number.
ctrl <- trainControl(method="repeatedcv", number = 10, repeats = 3, classProbs=FALSE)
knnFit <- train(as.factor(class) ~ ., data = training, method = "knn", trControl = ctrl, preProcess = c("center","scale"), tuneLength = 10)
# The results
knnFit
